```c
// Without dependency injection
class Logger {
    public function log($message) {
        // Do something with the message
    }
}

class User {
    private $logger;

    public function __construct(Logger $logger) {
        $this->logger = $logger;
    }

    public function doSomething() {
        // Do something interesting
        $this->logger->log("Something interesting happened!");
    }
}

// With dependency injection
class Logger {
    public function log($message) {
        // Do something with the message
    }
}

class User {
    private $logger;

    public function __construct(Logger $logger) {
        $this->logger = $logger;
    }

    public function doSomething() {
        // Do something interesting
        $this->logger->log("Something interesting happened!");
    }
}

// In your main program
$logger = new Logger();
$user = new User($logger);
$user->doSomething();
```
In this example, the "Logger" class is a dependency of the "User" class. Without dependency injection, the "User" class would create its own instance of the "Logger" class, which would tightly couple the two classes. With dependency injection, the "User" class receives its instance of the "Logger" class from an external source, which makes the "User" class more flexible and reusable.

This is just a simple example, but the principles of dependency injection can be applied to more complex systems as well. Dependency injection is a powerful design pattern that can help to create more modular, flexible, and maintainable code.

